            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this inflation calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool uses the U.S. Consumer Price Index for All Urban
                Consumers (CPI-U, all items, not seasonally adjusted) to
                estimate how the buying power of a dollar changes over time. You
                enter a dollar amount and two years; the calculator scales the
                amount by the ratio of CPI in those years.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formula</p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul class="list-disc pl-5">
                  <li>
                    <strong>CPI<sub>from</sub></strong> = CPI-U in the original
                    year
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>CPI<sub>to</sub></strong> = CPI-U in the target year
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>A<sub>from</sub></strong> = amount in original-year
                    dollars
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-1">
                  Then the equivalent amount in target-year dollars is:
                </p>
                <p
                  class="font-mono text-xs bg-white inline-block px-2 py-1 rounded border border-gray-200"
                >
                  A<sub>to</sub> = A<sub>from</sub> × (CPI<sub>to</sub> /
                  CPI<sub>from</sub>)
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>The calculator also reports:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cumulative inflation</strong> between the two years
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average annual inflation rate</strong> over the period
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Change in buying power</strong> (how much more or less
                  your money can buy)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Average annual inflation rate</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose the price level rises from CPI<sub>from</sub> to CPI<sub
                  >to</sub
                >
                over <em>n</em> years. The average annual inflation rate
                <em>r</em> is the compound growth rate that links the two:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p
                  class="font-mono text-xs bg-white inline-block px-2 py-1 rounded border border-gray-200"
                >
                  (1 + r)<sup>n</sup> = CPI<sub>to</sub> / CPI<sub>from</sub>
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1">So:</p>
                <p
                  class="font-mono text-xs bg-white inline-block px-2 py-1 rounded border border-gray-200"
                >
                  r = (CPI<sub>to</sub> / CPI<sub>from</sub>)<sup>1/n</sup> − 1
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>What is inflation?</h2>
              <p>
                Inflation is the rate at which the general level of prices for
                goods and services rises over time. When prices go up, each
                dollar buys fewer goods and services than before – the
                <strong>purchasing power</strong> of money falls.
              </p>
              <p>
                Economists usually measure inflation using price indexes such as
                the Consumer Price Index (CPI), the Personal Consumption
                Expenditures (PCE) price index, or GDP deflators. This
                calculator focuses on the U.S. CPI-U, which tracks the cost of a
                fixed basket of goods and services for urban consumers.
              </p>

              <h3>Why CPI-U?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  It is the most widely cited U.S. inflation measure (used by
                  the Bureau of Labor Statistics and many official calculators).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Long historical series are available, allowing comparisons
                  back many decades.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It covers a broad basket of everyday goods and services.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <p>Here are some ways to read the output of the calculator:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>“Equivalent in today’s dollars”</strong> – If you
                  enter a past year as the “from” year and a recent year as the
                  “to” year, the result tells you how much money you would need
                  today to have the same purchasing power.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>“Real value of future dollars”</strong> – If you enter
                  a future year as the “to” year (using projected CPI), the
                  result shows what a future nominal amount is worth in today’s
                  dollars.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cumulative inflation</strong> – A cumulative inflation
                  of 200% means prices roughly tripled over the period.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average annual inflation</strong> – This is the
                  smoothed yearly rate that would produce the same overall
                  change if it occurred every year.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool uses CPI-U for “all items”; your personal inflation
                  may differ depending on what you buy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It assumes you are comparing annual average CPI values, not
                  month-specific values.
                </li>
                <li>
                  For the most recent and future years, CPI values may be
                  estimates and will be updated as new data are released.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Inflation is only one factor in financial planning; wages,
                  taxes, and investment returns also matter.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is this calculator official?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This is an independent educational tool that uses CPI-U data
                and standard formulas similar to those used by official
                calculators (such as those from the U.S. Bureau of Labor
                Statistics or Federal Reserve Banks), but it is not an official
                government product.
              </p>

              <h3>How often is the CPI data updated?</h3>
              <p>
                The Bureau of Labor Statistics typically releases CPI data
                monthly. This calculator is designed so that the CPI table can
                be updated periodically to reflect the latest annual averages.
                Small differences from other calculators may occur if they use
                slightly different data vintages or monthly vs. annual CPI.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for non-U.S. inflation?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is specifically based on U.S. CPI-U. For
                other countries, you should use inflation data from your
                national statistics office, central bank, or international
                sources such as the World Bank, IMF, or OECD.
              </p>

              <h3>What’s the difference between nominal and real values?</h3>
              <p>
                A <strong>nominal</strong> amount is the number printed on a
                paycheck or price tag in a given year. A
                <strong>real</strong> amount adjusts for inflation so that
                values from different years can be compared in constant
                purchasing-power terms. This calculator converts nominal amounts
                into real equivalents across years.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I compare investment returns to inflation?</h3>
              <p>
                You can approximate your <strong>real return</strong> by
                subtracting the average inflation rate from your average nominal
                investment return. For example, if your portfolio returned 7%
                per year and inflation averaged 3% per year, your real return
                was roughly 4% per year. Use the “Show real return vs.
                inflation” toggle to see this comparison for your chosen period.
              </p>
